Goessel FFA
September 5 at 8:20 PM ·

***The box has been moved to the main GHS entrance due to the weather**

We are collecting items to send to ag. programs and FFA members and families who have been effected by Hurricane Laura. Below is a list of items they are asking for. Please drop off donations at the ag. building between 8:00 and 4:00 any day next week Tuesday-Friday. There will be a large box by the west Ag Shop door.

All items need to be in by noon Friday, September 11. For more information, please see the Louisiana State FFA website. Please help us join other FFA chapters in Kansas to fill our box!

post_text:
A few updates for this evening's preview.

The HS cheerleaders will be announced at 8:00 PM followed by a few routines.

Rows have been marked for social distancing, please honor those who desire to keep their space between family groups.

We have some construction on our east HS bathrooms, these are not available and you will need to use the west annex bathrooms or those by the office.

We will not be doing temperature checks at the football field. Our thermometers were reading Mr. Lightner at 122 degrees yesterday...that's a little warm! Masks are required inside and in congested areas around the stadium.

See you this evening!

post_text:
Fall Sports Preview is tomorrow! Please arrive no earlier than 15 minutes prior to your event.

For volleyball, you may enter either the east or west activity doors. Masks are required, your temperature will be taken (must be less than100.4) and sanitizer will be available. The JH will be in the JH gym at 3:45 and HS in the HS gym at 6:30.

For football, please come through west gate. You must wear a mask during the entry process and it is encouraged to remain on while in the stands. Your temperature will be taken as well. JH at 4:30 and HS at 7:30. This will be the first time for our new process so please be patient as we hope to smooth out the details prior to next week's events.

Calling all Goessel parents and community members!!
The Goessel Bluebird Backers Booster Club is inviting you to join us in support of our 2020-2021 school year! The Bluebird Backers is an organization that raises funds and organizes people to support our Goessel JH and HS students and staff.
We have begun our annual membership drive and you are invited to get involved! You can become a donating member at various levels and get perks! You can also donate your time and energy with different committees. Please see the flyers for family or business membership and the google form to get plugged in to committees!

Please join us next Tuesday, August 11 at 7:00 in the High School library for our first meeting of the year! We'll discuss plans for the upcoming year and would love to have many folks involved!

Questions??
Contact Amy Flaming
flaminga@usd411.org
316-772-6183

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1WpoirH1E_3GpHvz9ad4TgJgzoXvTys3ytNp0r1pNXX8/viewform?edit_requested=true

post_text: After qualifying to compete at FCCLA National Leadership Conference, Brooke Nafziger, Kaleigh Guhr, and Rachael Zogleman submitted their STAR Event projects via video recordings. NLC was held virtually this year, and the girls received their results at the end of July. Brooke received a gold medal for her Hospitality, Tourism, and Recreation event in which she created a recreational business, "Camp Create." Kaleigh and Rachael received a silver medal for their "Go For the Gold" Olympics-themed project. All three showed great leadership and perseverance with their FCCLA events this year.

Ryan Hoopes‎Goessel Girls Basketball
August 5 at 2:08 PM ·

Congrats to these girls for winning the basketball minutes challenge this summer. The girls were challenged to record their minutes practicing outside of what we did as a team. Lizzie came in 1st with 3815 minutes, Cheyenne was 2nd with 3519 minutes, Braylyn was 3rd with 1747 minutes, Hailey (not pictured) was 4th with 1110 minutes, and Jaicee was 5th with 835 minutes. Congrats on your hard work ladies! Keep it up!!!

post_text: MCSEC has an immediate opening for a para position at Goessel Elementary School. This position is approximately 33 hours a week. Interested candidates can request an application from either the MCSEC office 620-382-2858, or e-mail pputter@mcsec.org. Please specify interest in the Goessel Elementary position. MCSEC is an Equal Opportunity Employer.

The Hillsboro Hospital is offering sport physicals for $10 on August 3 and August 10 from 5:00-8:00 PM. No appointment is needed, just arrive at the hospital on those days. Transportation from Goessel High School is available on both evenings departing at 4:30 PM from the east doors of the high school. Click on this link and please use this form to sign up to ride school transportation. Physicals are required for any student in grades 6-12 who is interested in participation in a sport at Goessel Jr/Sr High School this year.

The history on the physical form (available at www.usd411.org or at either building's office) needs to be filled out prior to arrival and parents are welcome to attend. Bring $10 cash or a check made out to Hillsboro Hospital. Contact Brian Lightner (lightnerb@usd411.org) with any questions.

post_text: This evening at 8:20, four of our senior class tracksters participated in a medley relay for their final high school track meet with a goal of completing it in under 20 minutes and 20 seconds. They were awarded a first place trophy for winning the meet :) Congrats Bluebirds!

post_text: On this Tuesday, May 19th, on what would have been a normal day of wrapping up a school year for students and staff, we want to take a moment to say a big THANK YOU! The last quarter of this school year has been turned upside down by COVID 19, but the real story is the resilience and persistence of our parents, students and staff to continue educating our students at home. We want to take a moment to acknowledge you and express our sincere appreciation. We all hope that next year we can start out the school year in a more normal situation. Sincerely Dr. Fast and Mr. Boden.

post_text:
During a class meeting and through survey responses seniors overwhelmingly indicated they would like an in person ceremony that is as close to normal as possible at a later date. If the state continues to reopen as planned GHS Graduation will occur on July 18, 2020 at 4:00 PM in the HS gym.

Guidelines and requirements related to COVID-19 and its impact on Kansas are ever-changing. Throughout this process, we remain committed to the health and safety of our students and families in our community. Graduation ceremonies when they are able to be held will be conducted under the guidelines provided by the Kansas Department of Health and Environment (KDHE), Marion County Health Department (MCHD), Kansas State Department of Education (KSDE), and Governor Kelly’s Office.

We will do everything we can to proceed with an in person ceremony on July 18, however, attendance may be limited and there may be other restrictions in place at that time. We appreciate your flexibility and understanding in these challenging times as many things are simply beyond our control.

Families and Communities Together, Inc. (FACT) of Marion County, KS
April 15 at 12:07 PM ·

Families and Communities Together, Inc. (FACT) has recently received Relief Fund grants from the CKCF to help families needing food or groceries in the Hillsboro, Peabody, and Goessel areas. If you are a family in those areas or know of someone in those towns that are in need food or grocery assistance, please contact FACT at 620-947-3184 (ext. 1011) or 620-877-0197. Because these are Relief Funds for food/groceries, it does not matter if the family has already applied to our Families Financial Assistance Network for emergency utilities/rent/services assistance in the last 12 months--we can and are happy to still help them with their grocery needs.

post_text:
Dear Parents,
As you are aware, Governor Laura Kelly has closed schools for the reminder of the school year in Kansas. Specifically, this means we will no longer have students attending the traditional classroom. We will however be transitioning to a teaching and learning model outside the regular classroom to support learning at home. March 23 our staff return from spring break. The week will be considered an ‘intermission’ in our school year so that our staff can ‘retool’ and begin working on ways we will deliver the curriculum to your home using a combination of methods. We be using both on line and traditional paper packet method of learning. Watch for communication from your child’s teacher about how this will be done. We will also be announcing a schedule for parents and students to pick up personal items as well as the necessary learning materials we will send home on March 30. We apologize for this dramatic change in your child’s education but we trust you understand this is in the interest of safety and wellness for everyone.
Sincerely
Mr Boden and Dr Fast

post_text: Today Governor Kelly announced the closure of Kansas schools for the remainder of the school year in an effort to protect students, staff and citizens from the spread of COVID 19. In the coming days our teaching staff will be working to implement new state guidelines on how we can support learning in a non traditional manner, outside the classroom. In addition, we will be releasing information on how we intend to continue supporting education through the home. Meanwhile we encourage you to follow state health guidelines on keeping your family healthy. Wash hands frequently, cover coughs, avoid contact with those showing flu like symptoms. We will continue to post updates as we know them. As our state motto says, ad astra per aspera, to the stars through difficulties. Together we will support each other and get through this.

In addition, we will be releasing information on how we intend to continue supporting education through the home. Meanwhile we encourage you to follow state health guidelines on keeping your family healthy. Wash hands frequently, cover coughs, avoid contact with those showing flu like symptoms. We will continue to post updates as we know them. As our state motto says, ad astra per aspera, to the stars through difficulties. Together we will support each other and get through this.

post_text: We appreciate the efforts of Tristen Cope, KSU Extension Department to come do a lesson with all of our students on the importance of good hand washing. She had a special cream that only appeared under a black light. Once students washed their hands they checked to see how thorough they had been. They learned that ‘splash and dash’ does not remove germs! We need to wash our hands vigorously with soap and water at least 30 seconds to really get our hands clean.

We are excited to host the regional finals this evening beginning at 6:00 PM when the Rural Vista girls, ranked #3 in 1A take on Little River! Following the girls' championship, the Goessel boys will represent the home town as they take on the #9 rank Little River Redskins! Doors open at 5:00, if you can't make it to the game, catch it online at the link below or on on air at 106.1! Go Bluebirds!!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=36X2cG7g0cg

post_text: Our FFA held a Drive Your Tractor to School day and parked several at the grade school. Our students enjoyed looking over both large and small, new and old tractors. Thank you to the FFA members for bringing these tractors and helping us to better understand and appreciate the importance of agriculture in our lives.

post_text: The second graders had fun reenacting the Liberal and Olney Pancake race in PE today! Students had to dress up then run the court and flip the pancake and hand it off to the next runner. Even Mrs Churchill and Mrs Hiebert got into the fun! The winner? Everyone!

Due to the weather and road conditions, the HS girls' regional game at Elyria has been postponed and will be played tomorrow evening, February 26 beginning at 7:00.

We understand this is not ideal on a Wednesday night and appreciate your understanding and flexibility as the post-season games need to be played before subsequent rounds begin.

Good luck ladies!

post_text: The GHS Choir will perform at KMEA this Friday, Feb. 28 at 10:15am. The choir has been working very hard to prepare for this performance, and is excited to share their work! The performance is at the Hyatt Regency (Wichita) Ballrooms D-H, and is free and open to the public. Please note that parking at KMEA is packed - plan on parking by at least 10am to allow time to get into the Hyatt. Mr. Unruh and the GHS Choir thanks you for your support!
